explanation: OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro) — The macro is invoked directly on both parameters. It must be inspected to ensure it does not assign to or otherwise modify the parameter variables (e.g., "sock_id = ..." or "sock_name = ...") when expanded. A macro can hide assignments that would violate the MISRA rule. OS_ObjectIdFindByName (function) — Called with sock_name and sock_id; although a callee cannot change the caller's pointer variable unless the caller's address is passed, you must check its prototype/implementation to confirm it is not called in a way that would take the address of the parameter (e.g., &sock_id) after macro expansion, and to validate that its parameter types match (const-ness) so no hidden casts/assignments to the passed-in parameter occur. LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE (constant/macro) — Needed to resolve which overload/behavior of OS_ObjectIdFindByName is used (the object-type argument can affect internal code paths and therefore whether any wrapper macros change how parameters are passed). osal_id_t (typedef) — The declared type of sock_id; inspect to ensure it is indeed a pointer type (osal_id_t *) and not redefined in a way that would make sock_id a non-pointer or an alias with different semantics that could affect whether the function modifies the parameter itself. int32 (typedef) — The return type of the function; include to fully resolve any macros or inline functions used by OS_CHECK_POINTER that may interact with return semantics (e.g., early returns). OS_printf (function) — Frequently used by checking macros for logging inside OS_CHECK_POINTER; include to see whether the macro expands to a construct that could modify parameters (e.g., via nested macros that take parameter addresses) or otherwise affect analysis. OS_INVALID_POINTER (error-code macro/constant) — Likely used by OS_CHECK_POINTER for early return; include to resolve the macro expansion and ensure the macro does not perform assignments to the parameters as part of error handling.
